"{\"uid\": \"wandtv.com-news-noah-lyles-taken-off-track-in-wheelchair-moments-after-winning-bronze-at-paris-olympics-article_0fa3bbf8-55c0-11ef-b030-9f0a7c8dc17a.html\", \"text\": \"    Noah Lyles, of the United States, lies on the track following the men's 200-meters final at the 2024 Summer Olympics, Thursday, Aug. 8, 2024, in Saint-Denis, France. (AP Photo/Petr David Josek)  Noah Lyleswasdiagnosed with COVID-19two days before winning bronze in the men's 200m at the Paris Olympics, his mother told NBC. The running star left the track in a wheelchair with medical staff, then returned to speak on live TV.  The Alexandria, Virginia, track starran the men's 200m with a time of 19.70 on Thursday, then lay down on the ground. He continued sitting while medical attendants brought him water. A short time later, he left the track in a wheelchair.  Lewis Johnson provides an update on Noah Lyles' condition after he received medical attention following the 200m final.#ParisOlympics\\ud83d\\udcfa NBC & Peacockpic.twitter.com/3qRHsNe4JE  NBC's Lewis Johnson reported on the track broadcast that Lyles' mother confirmed the COVID diagnosis.  \\\"I ran into his mom Keisha Caine Bishop who was distraught trying to find him as well,\\\" Johnson said. \\\"We found Noah Lyles in medical, they are being tended to and she did confirm that Noah had been diagnosed with COVID two days ago.\\\"  Several minutes later, Lyles came out and spoke to Johnson during his broadcast.  \\\"Yeah I woke up early, about 5 a.m. on Tuesday morning and I just was feeling really horrible. I knew it was more than just being sore from the [100m race]. Woke up the doctors, and we tested, and unfortunately, it came up that I was positive for COVID. My first thought was not to panic, thinking, I have been in worse situations, I have run with worse conditions,\\\" he said.  Lyles previously said he has asthma, whichthe CDC has saidcan put people \\\"at increased risk for getting very sick from COVID-19.\\\"  Lyles won gold in the 100m race on Sunday. He had been open about trying to win gold in both the 200m and 100m races.  This story first appeared onNBCChicago.com.  Copyright \\u00a9 2024 NBCUniversal Media, LLC. All rights reserved  Your browser is out of date and potentially vulnerable to security risks.We recommend switching to one of the following browsers:\"}"